		<h4> PlantFuncSSRs: Plant functional SSRs for biodiversity and ecological explorations </h4>
		
		<span class="tab"></span>Recently, microsatellites or simple sequence repeats (SSRs) have been linked to putative 
functional domains; classifying them into a new class of functional markers called simple 

sequence repeats functional domains markers (SSR-FDMs) in model and non-model species (Yu 

et al., 2010; Bhattacharyya et al., 2014). Realizing the wide importance of SSRs, several online 

repositories and data mining tools have been developed to address the need for on-line mining of 

these markers such as UgMicroSatDb (Aishwarya and Sharma, 2008), SSR Biome and SSR 

taxonomy (Jewell et al., 2006), PlantMarkers (Rudd et al., 2005), MoccaDB (Plechakova et al., 

2009), CicArMiSatDB (Doddamani et al., 2014), and for Coffee ESTs (Poncet et al., 2006) have 

been developed to assist the mining of the SSRs. However, the functional classification of SSRs 

has not been studied in detailed.
</div></div>

<div class="col-md-12 text-justify">
			<div class="col-md-6">
				<p class="big"> </p>
<span class="tab"></span> PlantFuncSSRs provides a platform for the wide exploration of 

functional repeats available across wide range of plant species. Transcript assemblies present an 

important source of information for developing genic microsatellite markers. Next generation 

sequencing provides a cost-efficient way of transcript identification and facilitates the 

development of transcript based SSR markers for model and non-model species, which has 

resulted in rapid increases in the data made available online. However, much of this data is 

scattered across numerous websites and has not been mined or annotated for the identification of 

SSRs. Recently, there have been some efforts to consolidate such data for example TropiTree 

(<a href="http://bioinf.hutton.ac.uk/tropiTree" target="_blank">http://bioinf.hutton.ac.uk/tropiTree</a>) is a repository displaying the mined SSRs from NGS 

transcript assemblies for 24 tropical plants. PlantFuncSSRs was constructed with the aim of 

providing a standalone platform for the exploration of functional SSRs from the expressed 

portions of the genome as well as online platform for mining the SSRs either from the transcripts 

or the NGS reads of the transcriptome. To integrate previously published plant expressed 

sequence tags (ESTs) data, all Putative Unique Transcripts (PUTs) representing 273 transcript 

assemblies were downloaded from PlantGDB (Version release 187) available from 

<a href="http://www.plantgdb.org/" target="_blank">http://www.plantgdb.org/</a> (Dong et al., 2004).  Additionally, version control 74 NGS 

transcriptomes available at PhytoMetaSync (<a href="http://www.phytometasyn.ca" target="_blank">http://www.phytometasyn.ca</a>) (Facchini et al., 2012; 

Xiao et al., 2013), 14 medicinal plant transcriptomes available from MPGR 

(<a href="http://medicinalplantgenomics.msu.edu" target="_blank">http://medicinalplantgenomics.msu.edu</a>) (Góngora-Castillo et al., 2012; Góngora-Castillo and 

Buell CR, 2013) and 3 ecotype specific <i>Brachypodium sylvaticum</i> transcriptomes available from 

<a href="http://jaiswallab.cgrb.oregonstate.edu/genomics" target="_blank">http://jaiswallab.cgrb.oregonstate.edu/genomics</a> (Fox et al., 2013) were downloaded, 

representing a total of 364 plant species. 

